When you say **C++ programming techniques**, you’re asking about *how expert developers actually write code*—not just syntax, 
but **approaches, idioms, and patterns** used in real-world C++.

Here’s a **well-structured list of important C++ programming techniques**

---

# 1. RAII (Resource Management Technique)

Core C++ philosophy

* Tie resource lifetime to object lifetime
* Avoid manual `new/delete`

std::unique_ptr<int> p = std::make_unique<int>(10);


✔ Prevents memory leaks automatically

---

# 2. Value Semantics vs Reference Semantics

* Prefer **value semantics** (safe & predictable)
* Use references/pointers only when needed

void process(const std::string& s); // efficient + safe

---

# 3. Move Semantics (Performance Technique)

👉 Avoid unnecessary copies

std::vector<int> v = createVector(); // move instead of copy

✔ Important for high-performance systems

---

# 4. Generic Programming (Templates)

👉 Write reusable code

template<typename T>
T add(T a, T b) {
    return a + b;
}

✔ Used heavily in STL

---

# 5. Compile-Time Programming

👉 Shift work from runtime to compile time

constexpr int square(int x) {
    return x * x;
}

✔ Faster execution

---

# 6. STL-Based Programming

👉 Don’t reinvent the wheel

std::sort(v.begin(), v.end());

✔ Use algorithms + containers effectively

---

# 7. Algorithmic Thinking (with STL)

👉 Combine STL + logic

std::transform(v.begin(), v.end(), v.begin(),
               [](int x){ return x * x; });

---

# 8. Lambda Expressions (Modern C++)

👉 Inline behavior

auto sum = [](int a, int b) { return a + b; };

✔ Cleaner than function pointers

---

# 9. Smart Pointer Technique

👉 Replace raw pointers

* `unique_ptr` → single ownership
* `shared_ptr` → shared ownership

✔ Safer memory handling

---

# 10. Const-Correctness

👉 Make code predictable

int get() const;

✔ Prevent accidental modification

---

# 11. Defensive Programming

👉 Handle edge cases

* Check null pointers
* Validate input
* Avoid undefined behavior

---

# 12. Separation of Interface & Implementation

👉 Clean design

// header (.h)
class Engine;

// source (.cpp)
class Engine { ... };

---

# 13. Design Patterns Usage

👉 Structured problem solving

* Factory
* Strategy
* Observer
* Command

---

# ⚡ 14. Zero-Cost Abstraction

👉 C++ philosophy

* Abstraction should not add runtime cost
* Templates + inline functions

---

# 15. Idiomatic C++ (Modern Style)

👉 Write “C++ way”, not C-style

❌ Avoid:
int* p = new int;

✔ Prefer:
auto p = std::make_unique<int>();

---

# 16. Copy Elision & NRVO Awareness

👉 Let compiler optimize

return obj; // no copy in modern C++

---

# 17. Policy-Based Design (Advanced)

👉 Behavior via templates

template<typename Strategy>
class Engine : public Strategy {};

✔ Compile-time flexibility
---

# 18. CRTP (Compile-Time Polymorphism)

👉 Faster than virtual functions

template<typename T>
class Base {
public:
    void interface() {
        static_cast<T*>(this)->implementation();
    }
};

---

# 19. Modular Programming

👉 Break system into components

* Engine
* UI
* Data layer

✔ Useful for your console engine projects

---

# 20. Build & Dependency Management

👉 Real-world technique

* Use **CMake**
* Separate modules properly

---

# Simple Way to Remember

👉 Good C++ code uses:

* **RAII + STL + Templates + Smart pointers**

---

# If You Want to Level Up

* CRTP + Policy-based design
* STL internals
* Memory optimization
* Event-driven architecture

